Trade war between the U.S. and China: What accounts for China's unprecedented growth?¶

China's explosive economic power has been a concern for many Americans, as the U.S.'s massive trade deficit to China is in the hundreds of billions (USD) and continues to grow. U.S. President Donald J. Trump and Chinese President Xi Jinping are at odds, with both countries raising protective tariffs from 2018 onwards which seem to remove the conflict further from resolution. This clashing between the two economic powerhouses of the world casts uncertainty over the global economy at large. The following questions are relevant towards understanding this crisis:

What is the extent of the difference between the U.S. and Chinese trade economies?¶

To answer this, we explore:

  1. How has China's trade changed historically (1990-present) to its present state?
  2. How has U.S. trade changed changed historically (1990-present) to its present state?

We will address these questions using the World Development Indicators dataset available from Kaggle.

First, we simplify and clean up our dataset for this specific inquiry.

Since the dataset contains data on "regions" we don't need, let's delete all rows which refer to areas that aren't countries. We rely on help from this datahub.io dataset which contains valid country codes.

In [4]:
country_codes = pd.read_csv('./country-codes.csv')
country_codes = country_codes['ISO3166-1-Alpha-3']
countries_in_raw = pd.Series(raw['CountryCode'].unique().tolist())
countries_toDropFrom_raw = (list(set(countries_in_raw) - set(country_codes)))
raw = raw[~raw['CountryCode'].isin(countries_toDropFrom_raw)]
raw.head(5)

Next, we begin some preliminary analysis.

Analyzing Chinese and US trade over time¶

First, let's focus our dataset on Chinese trade. We need to filter the country and also filter out which entries are Exports versus Imports.

In [13]:
chn_data = stage1[stage1['CountryCode'].str.match('CHN')]
chn_data_exports = chn_data[chn_data['IndicatorName'].str.contains('Exports')]
chn_data_imports = chn_data[chn_data['IndicatorName'].str.contains('Imports')]

Let's take a look at the following plot.

In [14]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))

plt.plot(chn_data_exports['Year'].values, chn_data_exports['Value'].values)
plt.plot(chn_data_imports['Year'].values, chn_data_imports['Value'].values)

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Trillions USD')

plt.title('Chinese Trade, 1990-2015')

plt.legend(['Exports','Imports'])

plt.show()

We see an impressive upward trend for both Chinese imports and exports, but a clear positive trade surplus opening up after the early 2000s. This surplus persisted despite dips in both exports and imports around the 2008 financial crisis.

We can repeat this analysis for the US data to observe US trade over the same time frame.

In [15]:
usa_data = stage1[stage1['CountryCode'].str.match('USA')]
usa_data_exports = usa_data[usa_data['IndicatorName'].str.contains('Exports')]
usa_data_imports = usa_data[usa_data['IndicatorName'].str.contains('Imports')]

plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))

plt.plot(usa_data_exports['Year'].values, usa_data_exports['Value'].values)
plt.plot(usa_data_imports['Year'].values, usa_data_imports['Value'].values)

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Trillions USD')

plt.title('US Trade, 1990-2015')

plt.legend(['Exports','Imports'])

plt.show()

Contrarily, we see a huge trade deficit opening up in the US from the 1990s onward. It persists through the 2008 recession, and in the present day the US trade deficit appears larger than the Chinese trade surplus.

In [16]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))

plt.plot(chn_data_exports['Year'].values, chn_data_exports['Value'].values, color='b')
plt.plot(chn_data_imports['Year'].values, chn_data_imports['Value'].values, color='b', ls='dashed')
plt.plot(usa_data_exports['Year'].values, usa_data_exports['Value'].values, color='r')
plt.plot(usa_data_imports['Year'].values, usa_data_imports['Value'].values, color='r', ls='dashed')

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Trillions USD')

plt.title('US & Chinese Trade, 1990-2015')

plt.legend(['Chinese Exports','Chinese Imports', 'US Exports', 'US Imports'])

plt.show()

Overlaying these two graphs, we can see the difference in how the two economies' trade have changed over a 25-year span.

As mentioned earlier, the US deficit is larger than the Chinese surplus. Both economies took a dip in the 2008 recession, but America's was noteiceably larger. And, whereas the US grew towards a larger deficit post-2008, China grew to a larger surplus post-2008. Around 2014, we see the Chinese exports catching up to the US exports.

All in all, the Chinese surplus has grown persistently, and Chinese exports and imports seem to both have increased in the post-2008 world. This suggests that the financial recession, in conjunction with other factors, seemed to catalyze, or at least encourage, further surplus growth.

By contrast, the US has had a consistent deficit from even before the recession, despite persistently higher exports and imports. Perhaps the US economic crash in 2008 was a symptom, and not a cause, or persistent trade deficits. Despite the US economy's recovery, the deficit continues to widen.

What explains the Chinese trade surplus?¶

Many economic indicators can be used to explain why the Chinese economy has entered into such a large surplus compared to the more developed US economy.

For this, we will split our analysis on exports and imports for both China and the US, and then compare the results.

Chinese exports¶

We hypothesize that, in general, higher exports are a result of a larger working population and higher education levels, which both encourage productivity.

Let's look for a relevant indicator for the Chinese workforce.

The above scatter plot and calculated correlation coefficients give us the following insights:

  1. There is a somewhat strong positive correlation (0.761) between secondary education enrollment and exports. Note that this correlation is weaker than the one between labor force and exports.
  2. Secondary education enrollment grew roughly by 93,400,000 students per year over the 23-year period, although the growth was far from linear. The downward trend in enrollment from 2008 onwards is strange - would the 2008 recession really have impacted high-school enrollment? It seems likely that the larger trend of families having less children in the 21st century impacted the number of younger students going to secondary schools. This question would benefit from a separate analysis linked to other factors, such as Chinese population control policy.

All in all, the change in labor force seems to be a stronger predictor of trade exports than the enrollment in secondary education.

Here we see the Chinese leading the US in both labor force and secondary education enrollment, both symptoms of a massively larger population size, and both pointing towards higher productivity.

Thus, it is supported that China's exports have risen dramatically, contributing to that country's trade surplus, in contrast to the US's stagnating labor force & secondary education enrollment, which could have contributed to that country's trade deficit.

Chinese imports¶

What indicators are related to imports? We hypothesize that imports increase when a country becomes more consumerist, and two symptoms of a more consumerist society are higher CO2 consumption and mobile cellular subscriptions.

We repeat the process carried out for Chinese exports above.

Comparing Chinese and US CO2 emissions and cell phone subscriptions¶

In [55]:

Interestingly, we see the Chinese CO2 emissions skyrocket in the early 2000s, surpassing the stagnating US emissions in 2005.

In [56]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))

plt.title('Chinese v. US cell subscriptions, 1990-2014')
plt.legend(['Chinese cell subs','US cell subs'])
plt.show()

Both the US and China's cell subscriptions have grown at similar rates, with the US still edging out China by a small margin. But both countries are near 100 percent of people having cell phone subscriptions, so this information is not too useful at the moment.

Altogether, it is not supported that an increase in consumerism via higher CO2 emissions and cellular subscriptions can properly explain the Americans' higher levels of imports or the American trade deficit.

This is especially true of CO2 emissions. The US's lower CO2 emission level than that of China (again, probably attributed to China's larger population) did not correlate strongly with higher imports, which contributed to the US's trade deficit. Conversely, higher CO2 emissions in China did strongly correlate with higher levels of imports, but China's trade surplus still stands. In fact, these results seem counterintuitive to the fact that China is in surplus but the US is in deficit.

This analysis on imports was not conclusive as to why the US is at a deficit and China is at a surplus.

Altogether, while our indicators gave varying levels of support to answering why the US and China have such different trade levels, it is important to note that these correlations are undoubtedly related to rising populations. Let's look briefly at these population levels.

The US and China in a global trade economy¶

What about the rest of the world? How do the US and China compare? For this, we return to the stage1 DataFrame set up before which had country code, imports/exports, year, and value.

First, let's set up a "Net Trade" column.

In [59]:
stage1_exports = stage1[stage1['IndicatorName'].str.contains('Exports')]
stage1_imports = stage1[stage1['IndicatorName'].str.contains('Imports')]
stage1_netTrade = stage1_exports.merge(stage1_imports, on=['CountryCode', 'Year'], how='inner')
stage1_netTrade = stage1_netTrade.drop(['IndicatorName_x','IndicatorName_y'], axis=1)
stage1_netTrade.rename(columns={'Value_x':'Exports','Value_y':'Imports'}, inplace=True)
stage1_netTrade['NetTrade'] = stage1_netTrade['Exports'].values - stage1_netTrade['Imports'].values
stage1_netTrade.head(5)

In [60]:
stage1_netExports_yr = stage1_netTrade[['Year','Exports']].groupby('Year').sum()
stage1_netImports_yr = stage1_netTrade[['Year','Imports']].groupby('Year').sum()
stage1_netTrade_yr = stage1_netTrade[['Year','NetTrade']].groupby('Year').sum()

stage1_netTrade = stage1_netTrade.merge(stage1_netExports_yr, on='Year', how='inner')
stage1_netTrade.rename(columns={'Exports_x':'Exports','Exports_y':'TotalExports_Yr'}, inplace=True)
stage1_netTrade = stage1_netTrade.merge(stage1_netImports_yr, on='Year', how='inner')
stage1_netTrade.rename(columns={'Imports_x':'Imports','Imports_y':'TotalImports_Yr'}, inplace=True)
stage1_netTrade['ExportsShare'] = stage1_netTrade['Exports'].values / stage1_netTrade['TotalExports_Yr'].values
stage1_netTrade['ImportsShare'] = stage1_netTrade['Imports'].values / stage1_netTrade['TotalImports_Yr'].values
stage1_netTrade.head(5)

The preceding three bar charts illustrate the power of the US and Chinese economies. The two countries lead the world in both exports and imports, and all countries fall somewhere in between the two in terms of net trade.

We wish to visualize this global trade situation in a more compelling way. Let's use the package folium and a set of world coordinates to accomplish this.

In [67]:

Conclusion and Further Directions¶

In this analysis, we compared exports and imports in the US and China's trade economies. Then, we explored some possible correlating factors such as labor force population and CO2 emissions, ultimately giving us an idea of why China's exports are higher, but not supporting our inquiry about why the US's imports are higher. Finally, we saw how the world at large is situated amongst the US and China's two supereconomies, further suggesting the importance of the ongoing trade war between the two countries.

Where might China and the US's deficits go from here? Economists and statisticians alike would both scoff at what is presented below: linear regression of previous net trade of both countries. We make use of the sci-kit learn package.

In [68]:
stage1_netTrade_chn = stage1_netTrade[stage1_netTrade['CountryCode'].str.match('CHN')]
stage1_netTrade_usa = stage1_netTrade[stage1_netTrade['CountryCode'].str.match('USA')]

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

model_chn = LinearRegression()
model_chn.fit(stage1_netTrade_chn['Year'].values[:,np.newaxis], stage1_netTrade_chn['NetTrade'].values)

model_usa = LinearRegression()
model_usa.fit(stage1_netTrade_usa['Year'].values[:,np.newaxis], stage1_netTrade_usa['NetTrade'].values)

years_set_chn = stage1_netTrade_chn['Year'].values[:,np.newaxis]
years_set_usa = stage1_netTrade_usa['Year'].values[:,np.newaxis]

years_set_chn2 = pd.Series(range(2015,2040))[:,np.newaxis]
years_set_usa2 = pd.Series(range(2014,2038))[:,np.newaxis]

plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
plt.scatter(stage1_netTrade_chn['Year'].values, stage1_netTrade_chn['NetTrade'].values, color='r')
plt.plot(years_set_chn.tolist(), model_chn.predict(years_set_chn), color='r', ls='dashed')
plt.plot(range(2015,2040), model_chn.predict(years_set_chn2), color='r', ls='dashed')
plt.scatter(stage1_netTrade_usa['Year'].values, stage1_netTrade_usa['NetTrade'].values, color='b')
plt.plot(range(2014,2038), model_usa.predict(years_set_usa2), color='b', ls='dashed')
plt.plot(years_set_usa.tolist(), model_usa.predict(years_set_usa), color='b', ls='dashed')
plt.xlabel("Years")
plt.ylabel("Net trade, trillions of dollars")
plt.title("Chinese and US net trade extrapolated over 2015-2040")
plt.legend(['Chinese net trade, trendline','Chinese net trade','US net trade, trendline','US net trade'])
plt.axis([1990, 2040, -2e12, 2e12])
plt.show()

Although other regression models would have been more elegant, this graph at least shows the divergence between China's trade surplus and the US's trade deficit. It also shows the gap widening to what is potentially an over 2 trillion USD gap by 2040.

In conclusion, the US-Chinese trade war is important to the modern international trade system, and whatever happens will have intense global ramifications.

Future analytics could explore:

  1. Other economic indicators which are predictors of imports and exports
  2. Visualizing the history of the global trade economy with an interactive map to see trends in rising economies
  3. Using more elegant regression techniques to predict the future of the US-China trade imbalance.
